<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-export SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/evernote-export4.dtd">
<en-export export-date="20260611T073911Z" application="Evernote" version="11.9.1">
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20190604T032850Z</created>
    <updated>20230525T082351Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>a. Scanty endometrial tissue with suppurative exudates</div><div>b. Suggestive of actinomycosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows scanty endometrial glandular and stromal</div><div>tissue with heavy collections of neutrophilic exudate and</div><div>fibrinoid deposition. Presence of a few bacterial colonies</div><div>(sulphur granules) found at the center of the inflammatory</div><div>reaction, composed of basophilic radiating filaments are</div><div>seen, suggestive of actinomycosis.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>acute and chronic cervicitis. [CAI]</title>
    <created>20181019T111934Z</created>
    <updated>20260209T080732Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Uterus, cervix, biopsy --- Acute and chronic cervicitis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows ecto- and endocervical tissue with subepithelial infiltrate of mixed inflammatory cells. Intraepithelial neutrophilic infiltrate is also seen. No malignancy is observed.    </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20230208T043507Z</created>
    <updated>20230616T061808Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>acute chorioamnionitis.</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>Sections of the placenta shows neutrophils aggregating in</div><div>the subchorionoic fibrin, and some within connective tissue</div><div>layer of the chorion and amnion. (Maternal response, stage</div><div>2, intermediate). Scattered neutrophils within umbilical</div><div>vessel wall and abundant neutrophils located at the</div><div>periphery of the umbilical cord are seen. (Fetal response,</div><div>stage 1, early) No fungal element is demonstrated by PAS</div><div>stain.</div><div><br/></div><div>Blaustein p1472</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>adenocarcinoma. favor CCC</title>
    <created>20220301T043758Z</created>
    <updated>20230822T062709Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>adenocarcinoma. see NOTE.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows variably-sized tubules with intraluminal dense</div><div>eosinophilic secretions, composed of tumor cells including</div><div>some hobnail cells with moderate to marked nuclear atypia</div><div>and abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm.</div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: Based on the morphology and the immunophenotypes</div><div>(performed on S1101519C), it is an adenocarcinoma, most</div><div>likely clear cell carcinoma. However, a definite diagnosis</div><div>can only be made on the subsequent larger specimen, as the</div><div>tumor is not fully sampled.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Adenomatoid tumor</title>
    <created>20160715T030515Z</created>
    <updated>20241106T052216Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>adenomatoid tumor.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description: </div><div>There are multiple irregular spaces lined by flattened to cuboidal cells scattered between the myometrial bundles. These cells are positive for calretinin, suggesting an adenomatoid tumor.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>adenomyoma.</title>
    <created>20230327T014637Z</created>
    <updated>20231006T072724Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>adenomyoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows polypoid tissue composed of an admixture of morphologically benign endometrioid-type glands, endometrioid-type stroma, and smooth muscle.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the endometrioid-type stromal component is positive with CD10, and the smooth muscle component positive with desmin.                                      </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20200703T104206Z</created>
    <updated>20200703T104309Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>adult granulosa cell tumor.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The tumor invades the serosal and subserosal layer of</div><div>small intestine, and is composed neoplastic cells bearing</div><div>scant cytoplasm with round to oval nuclei, arranged in</div><div>solid, trabecular and insular patterns. Nulear grooves are</div><div>seen. Call-Exner bodies are also noted.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>AIS HPV-associated.</title>
    <created>20210917T100713Z</created>
    <updated>20250514T031121Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>adenocarcinoma in situ (AIS), HPV-associated.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows cervical tissue revealing adenocarcinoma in situ, with depleted mucin, nuclear hyperchromasia, apoptosis, and mitoses.</div><div>By immunohistochemistry, the dysplastic glandular cells are diffusely positive for p16 with high Ki-67 proliferation index.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>At least complex atypical hyperplasia, grade 1 adenocarcinoma cannot be excluded</title>
    <created>20180122T073955Z</created>
    <updated>20190131T030344Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><br/></div><div>Section shows endometrial tissue exhibiting complex hyperplasia featuring marked glandular complexity and crowding, with additional finding of cellular atypia.  </div><div><br/></div><div>Small foci of confluent, haphazard glandular pattern with merging of glnads and interconnecting gland lumens are seen. Grade 1 adenocarcinoma cannot be excluded. </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Atrophy</title>
    <created>20170707T051743Z</created>
    <updated>20251230T030345Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Atrophy.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows cervical tissue in which the squamous epithelium shows atrophic change. The squamous cells are hyperchromatic but uniform and evenly spaced without mitotic activity. Immunohistochemically, p16 is negative. The Ki-67 index shows no significant increase.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Atypical adenofibromatous tummor</title>
    <created>20161227T064934Z</created>
    <updated>20161227T064958Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows a polypoid lesion featuring cleft-like glands and polypoid stromal projections lined by benign endocervical epithelium. The underlying stroma is composed of uniform fibrous cells with presence of one mitotic figure, and focal periglandular cuffing. </div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the stromal cells are positive for CD10 and SMA, with periglandular condenstion highlighted by immunostains. </div><div><br/></div><div>Taken together, this is an atypical adenofibromatous tumor which shows a predominant features of adenofibroma with some worrisome features including periglandular cuffing and detectable mitotic activity. A hysterectomy is recommended to rule out the presence of abnormal areas indicative of adenosarcoma.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20170315T233510Z</created>
    <updated>20170315T233608Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Section shows endometrial tissue revealing atypical hyperplasia, which is characterized by glandular crowding with little intervening stroma and cellular atypia. Squamous morules are also seen.  </div><div><br/></div><div>A well-differentiated adenocarcinoma cannot be excluded.  Clinical correlation is highly recommended.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20210315T052933Z</created>
    <updated>20210315T052944Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Bartholin cyst.              </div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows cystic spaces lined by transitional, low cuboidal, or mucinous epithelium, with normal mucus glands adjacent to the cyst.</div><div><br/></div><div>     </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Breakdown (&amp;太碎無法評估)</title>
    <created>20160715T031431Z</created>
    <updated>20200604T071031Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><font style="font-size: 10pt;"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Blood clots with scanty endometrial tissue</span></font></div><div><font style="font-size: 10pt;"><span style="font-size: 10pt;"><br/></span></font></div><div><font style="font-size: 10pt;"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Microscopic description:</span></font></div><div><font style="font-size: 10pt;"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">It shows blood clot and fragmented endometrial tissue with stromal breakdown. The glandular density cannot be evaluated precisely due to fragmentation of specimen.</span></font></div><div><font style="font-size: 10pt;"><br/></font></div><div><font style="font-size: 10pt;"><br/></font></div><div><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Blood clots with scanty endometrial tissue</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Section shows blood clot and fragmented endometrial tissue with stromal cells aggregating into packed balls, separating from the glands. The glandular density cannot be evaluated due to fragmentation of specimen.</span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>carcinosarcoma MMMT</title>
    <created>20201225T024714Z</created>
    <updated>20201225T024738Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Carcinosarcoma (malignant mixed Mullerian tumor).</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC DESCRIPTION:</div><div>Sections show a tumor composed of a high-grade carcinoma,</div><div>which is difficult to subclassify, and homologous stromal</div><div>component. Squamous differentiation is also seen. The</div><div>endometrium shows atrophic change and is not involved by</div><div>tumor. Adenomyosis is identified adjacent to the tumor, and</div><div>is partially involved by tumor.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>(Carcinosarcoma is generally considered to be high grade</div><div>and it is not recommended to assign a histologic grade)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Careful monitoring / CIN2?</title>
    <created>20251009T032204Z</created>
    <updated>20251009T032229Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>COMMENT: The changes warrant careful monitoring due to the</div><div>focal features that raise concern for CIN2 but do not meet</div><div>the criteria.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20180328T015320Z</created>
    <updated>20200713T091206Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>cellular angiofibroma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows a well-demarcated, polypoid tumor lined by</div><div>squamous mucosa, which is uniformly cellular composed of</div><div>bland, spindle-shaged cells admixed with mast cells, and</div><div>small to medium-sized blood vessels.</div><div><br/></div><div>By immunohistochemistry, the tumor cells are positive for</div><div>ER, CD34 and desmin but not S100, Myogenin or myoD1.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20210204T032840Z</created>
    <updated>20210204T032846Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>chronic cervicitis with squamous metaplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows endocervical tissue with subepithelial infiltrate of chronic inflammatory cells and squamous metaplasia. No malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Chronic endometritis</title>
    <created>20170303T062102Z</created>
    <updated>20251223T031136Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Chronic endometritis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows endometrial glandular and stromal tissue with collections of neutrophils, histiocytes and scattered plasma cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE: An endometrial polyp or sampling of endometrium overlying leiomyoma may also contain plasma cells. Please correlate with clinical symptom.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CIN1</title>
    <created>20160715T030850Z</created>
    <updated>20180406T032726Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><ul><li>Section shows focal mild dysplasia of squamous epithelium confirmed by p16 and Ki-67.</li></ul><div><br/></div><ul><li>The cervical tissue shows the squamous epithelium focally replaced by dysplastic cells involving the innermost one-fourth of the epithelial thickness accompanied by koilocytosis. Chronic inflammatory infiltrate in the subepithelial tissue along with squamous metaplasia is also seen.</li></ul><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><ul><li>With anti-p16 immunostain, only few superfical cells present with positive reactivity</li></ul><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><ul><li>Staining for p16 is negative. The proliferation index as determined by Ki-67 is increased confined within basal and parabasal layers.</li></ul><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CIN1_Low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (LSIL)</title>
    <created>20170316T070759Z</created>
    <updated>20250319T025550Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (LSIL) (CIN1).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows parabasal hyperplasia confined to the lower</div><div>third of the epithelium, accompanied by koilocytotic atypia</div><div>of the upper layers.</div><div><br/></div><div>Staining for p16 is negative.</div><div>The Ki67 shows increased nuclear staining confined within basal and parabasal layer.</div><div><br/></div><div>Staining for p16 shows diffuse and strong positive over 1/3 layer of squamous epithelium.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CIN2</title>
    <created>20160715T030912Z</created>
    <updated>20241206T030842Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>High-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (HSIL) (CIN2).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The cervical tissue shows evidence of CIN2 in which the inner half of the epithelium is replaced by dysplastic cells, (which is also demonstrated by positive immunostaining for p16 and increased Ki-67 labeling index in the dysplastic cells.)</div><div>        </div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CIN3</title>
    <created>20160715T030921Z</created>
    <updated>20200817T100233Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">High-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (HSIL) (CIN3).</span></div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:<br/></div><div>Section shows full thickness immaturity of squamous epithelium, featuring irregular polarity, nuclear pleomorphism and presence of mitotic figures in the superficial layer. Atrophic change is also seen. Stainings for p16 and ki-67 support the diagnosis.</div><div> </div><div>Microscopic description:<br/></div><div>Section shows areas of full-layered dysplasia of squamous epithelium, featuring p16 immunoreactivity and high Ki-67 labeling index.</div><div>    </div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>complex atypical hyperplasia</title>
    <created>20160715T031030Z</created>
    <updated>20190131T030320Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><div>complex atypical hyperplasia.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows endometrial tissue exhibiting crowded aggregates of tubular or branching glands lined by columnar cells featuring focal cellular atypia with little intervening stroma.</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><hr/><div>Small foci of confluent glandular pattern with merging of glnads and interconnecting gland lumens are seen. Grade 1 adenocarcinoma cannot be excluded.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the atypical cells are positive for ER and PR.</div></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Complex hyperplasia without atypia, endometrium</title>
    <created>20160715T031004Z</created>
    <updated>20181203T065307Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Complex hyperplasia without atypia</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows endometrial tissue revealing closely packed endometrial glands with occasional back-to-back crowding with little intervening stroma. The nuclei are uniform in size and shape without overt atypia.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CON - HSIL [conization]</title>
    <created>20160715T030754Z</created>
    <updated>20251222T022841Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;">High-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (HSIL)/</span>Carcinoma in situ (CIS). _Margin____</div><div><br/></div><div>All tissue is submitted in 4 cassettes.</div><div>A1: 12-3 o'clock of cervix</div><div>A2:  3-6 o'clock of cervix</div><div>A3:  6-9 o'clock of cervix</div><div>A4:  9-12 o'clock of cervix</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections of the cervix shows the entire thickness of epithelium replaced by dysplastic squamous cells with extension into the underlying endocervical glands with partial or complete replacement by the dysplastic cells. No stromal invasion is seen. The surgical margin is free of tumor.</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font-family: &quot;Microsoft YaHei&quot;;"><span style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);">Section taken from the endocervix is unremarkable.</span></span></span></div><div><br/></div><div>Endocervical Margin: </div><div>Ectocervical Margin: </div><hr/><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Histologic type: high-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion </div><div>  (HSIL)/carcinoma in situ (CIS)</div><div>Tumor site: </div><div>  Left superior (anterior) quadrant (12 to 3 o'clock) </div><div>  Left inferior (posterior) quadrant (3 to 6 o'clock) </div><div>  Right inferior (posterior) quadrant (6 to 9 o'clock)</div><div>  Right superior (anterior) quadrant (9 to 12 o'clock)</div><div>Margin status: all margins negative for HSIL. </div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>condyloma acuminatum???.</title>
    <created>20220105T093021Z</created>
    <updated>20230711T023751Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>benign squamous epithelial lesion (see description).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows a tiny tissue fragment with vague papillary structure lined by squamous epithelium focally revealing koilocytic-like change. The differential diagnosis include condyloma acuminatum, and fibroepithelial polyp, which cannot be accurately distinguished in this limited specimen.</div><div>Please correlate clinically.</div><div>            </div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>condyloma/cervix</title>
    <created>20210312T021345Z</created>
    <updated>20250401T031122Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>exophytic low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (condyloma).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows parabasal hyperplasia confined to the lower third of the epithelium, accompanied by koilocytotic atypia of the upper layers. There is prominent papillary architecture in which the individual papillae are supported by a fibrovascular core.</div><div>Staining for p16 is focally positive.       </div><div>The Ki67 shows increased nuclear staining confined within basal and parabasal la    yer.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Confirmed, vaginal wall, colporrhaphy and repair of enterocele</title>
    <created>20160715T031333Z</created>
    <updated>20230906T060318Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>Section shows benign squamous mucosa and submucosal tissue. No evidence of malignancy.</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20190121T065241Z</created>
    <updated>20230801T074011Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>consistent with complete hydatidiform mole.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows hydropic villi with frequent central cisterns. Trophoblastic hyperplasia is seen. The villous stroma is myxoid with focally increased cellularity and karyorrhexis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the majority (>90%) of cytotrophoblasts and villous stromal cells are negative for p57, consistent with the diagnosis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Clinical correlation including serum test for hCG is recommended.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20220310T010649Z</created>
    <updated>20231114T075257Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>consistent with IUD-associated endometritis.</div><div><br/>
Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows endometrial tissue with infiltrate of mixed</div><div>inflammatory cells including plasma cells, admixed with</div><div>Actinomytotic granules highlighted by PAS.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20181123T014650Z</created>
    <updated>20230725T013853Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>consistent with retained placenta.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Sections show the presence of degenerated placental tissue with mixed inflammatory cell infiltration</div><div>and focal calcification. Hemorrhage and fibrin precipitation</div><div>are present. It is consistent with retained placenta.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>consistent with very early complete</title>
    <created>20190123T013145Z</created>
    <updated>20190123T013621Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>consistent with very early complete hydatidiform mole.</div><div><br/>
Microscopic description:<br/></div><div>Sections show villi of normal size with polypoid appearance</div><div>accompanied by mild trophoblastic hyperplasia and moderate</div><div>cytological atypia. The villous stroma is myxoid with</div><div>focally increased cellularity and karyorrhexis.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemically, the majority (>90%) of</div><div>cytotrophoblasts and villous stromal cells are negative for</div><div>p57. Ki67 index is high in cytotrophoblast. The overall</div><div>features are consistent with very early complete</div><div>hydatidiform mole.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>CXPO (CAI no SM) cxpocai</title>
    <created>20200924T030541Z</created>
    <updated>20240925T075901Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows polypoid or frond-like architecture containing columnar endocervical-type mucinous epithelium. The stroma is edematous and containing acute and chronic inflammatory cells. No malignancy is observed.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
