    <updated>20240410T090617Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>endometrial polyp with atypical stromal cells. see note.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:    </div><div>Section shows endometrial polyp focally containing stromal cells with markedly atypical symplastic-like nuclei.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, these stromal cells are positive for CD10 and focally positive for desmin but not CD68 or AE1/AE3.</div><div><br/></div><div>Note: Although studies with follow-up are limited, behavior appears to be indolent with no recurrences or progression to malignancy reported. Follow-up is suggested.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Endometrial polyp with focal complex hyperplasia,</title>
    <created>20160715T030640Z</created>
    <updated>20160715T030646Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>Section shows polypoid tissue lined by endometrial epithelium with glands set in a stroma with thick-walled blood vessels. There is focal complex hyperplasia revealing cribriform architecture without cellular atypia.</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Endometrial polyp, infarcted.</title>
    <created>20180316T055300Z</created>
    <updated>20180316T055345Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;">PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;">Uterus, cervix, polypectomy --- Endometrial polyp, infarcted.</span></div><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;"><br/></span></div><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;">Gross description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;">The specimen consists of _ pieces of polypoid tissue measuring up to  __cm.</span></div><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;">All for section.</span></div><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;"><br/></span></div><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;">Microscopic description:</span></div><div><span style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;">Section shows polypoid tissue with prominent infarction. It is focally lined by endometrial epithelium with hypersecretory glands set in a decidualized stroma and numerous blood vessels with acute inflammatory exudate. No malignancy is observed.</span></div><div><br style="font-family: Microsoft YaHei;" /></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>endometrioid carcinoma (cervix)</title>
    <created>20230323T052239Z</created>
    <updated>20230323T052300Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>endometrioid carcinoma. (see description)</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section reveals confluent glandular structures lined by columnar epithelium with loss of intervening stroma and forming villoglandular architecture. Intraluminal necrosis is also seen.</div><div>The overall features are indicative of endometrioid carcinoma, and extension from an endometrial tumor should be taken into consideration. Please correlate with clinical presentation.</div><div><br/></div><div>Immunohistochemical stains:</div><div>ER (Ab): Positive (80%, moderate)</div><div>PR (Ab): Positive (90%, strong)</div><div>P16: No overexpression.</div><div>Vimentin: Focally positive.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Endometrioid carcinoma (EM)</title>
    <created>20160715T030500Z</created>
    <updated>20251015T022632Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div style="display:none;--en-chs:&quot;&quot;"> </div><div>Endometrioid carcinoma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The endometrial tissue reveals confluent glandular structures lined by columnar epithelium with loss of intervening stroma and focal cribriform architecture. Intraluminal necrosis is also seen.</div><div>There is non-squamous solid growth pattern, accounting for</div><div>around ___% of total tumorous tissue in this specimen.</div><div><br/></div><div>1. ER (Ab): Positive / Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div>2. PR (Ab): Positive /Negative (  %, weak / moderate / strong)</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been reviewed by two pathologists.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Endometrioma</title>
    <created>20160715T030610Z</created>
    <updated>20220830T090953Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Endometrioma</div><div><br/></div><div>MICROSCOPIC FINDING:</div><div><span style="font-size: 14px; font-family: gotham, helvetica, arial, sans-serif;">Sections shows cystic lesions with variable destruction of its lining epithelium and with heavy accumulation of hemosiderin-laden macrophages in the stroma. There are occasional endometrial glandular linings and associated stroma identified.</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Endometriosis</title>
    <created>20160715T030600Z</created>
    <updated>20160715T030606Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note>
<div>Sections show ovarian tissue with cystic lesion lined by hemosiderin-laden macrophages and endometrial tissue.</div>
</en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Epithelioid leiomyoma</title>
    <created>20170207T123406Z</created>
    <updated>20170207T123414Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div><font size="2">Section shows well-circumscribed nodule withhin myometrium  composed of epithelioid cells <font style="font-size: 12px; font-family: Gotham;">with appreciable eosinophilic or clear cytoplasm and being positive for desmin, SMA and CD10 (focal). Neither cellular atypism nor mitosis is observed.</font></font><br/></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Fibroma, ovary</title>
    <created>20160715T031056Z</created>
    <updated>20260408T062722Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Fibroma.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>It shows ovarian tissue with tumor composed of uniform spindle cells bearing oval to spindle shaped nuclei in a collagenous stroma. Mitosis is hardly identified (_/10HFP). No cellular atypia is discerned.</div><div><br/></div><div><a href="evernote:///view/26224745/s227/e64c2370-e9c0-454d-a2c1-7a150dccac37#0fbca591-efd9-4ef5-af32-e34de6348332/c8311643-9c2f-4cb3-a1f0-5d2b68c95ae3/">Fibroma</a></div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>focal complex atypical hyperplasia with extensive squamous differentiation. see NOTE.</title>
    <created>20200615T072210Z</created>
    <updated>20200615T072234Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>PATHOLOGIC DIAGNOSIS:</div><div>Uterus, endometrium, diagnostic D &amp; C ---</div><div>focal complex atypical hyperplasia with extensive squamous differentiation. see NOTE.</div><div><br/></div><div>Gross description:</div><div>The specimen consists of multiple pieces of tissue measuring ___ gm in total.</div><div>All for section.</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows endometrial tissue predominantly lined by</div><div>squamoid cells with focal areas exhibiting</div><div>crowded aggregates of tubular or branching glands lined by columnar cells featuring focal cellular atypia with little intervening stroma.</div><div>Immunohistochemically, the squamoid cells are positive for ER, and p63 but not PR.</div><div><br/></div><div>NOTE:</div><div>Because the diagnosis depends on an evaluation of the glandular component, I cannot do any better than call it focal complex atypical hyperplasia with extensive squamous differentiation.</div><div>Repeat sampling for more specimen to exclude coexistent neoplasia is recommended.</div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>未命名記事</title>
    <created>20220422T023737Z</created>
    <updated>20220422T023748Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.win</source>
      <source-application>evernote.win32</source-application>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Focal high-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion (HSIL) (CIN2).</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>The cervical tissue shows predominant LSIL with</div><div>focal evidence of CIN2 in which the inner half of the</div><div>epithelium is replaced by dysplastic cells, which is also</div><div>demonstrated by positive immunostaining for p16 and</div><div>increased Ki-67 labeling index in the dysplastic cells.</div><div><br/></div><div>(This case has been peer reviewed by two doctors.)</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Focal simple hyperplasia without atypia</title>
    <created>20160715T031021Z</created>
    <updated>20241106T051629Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
      <source>desktop.mac</source>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>focal simple hyperplasia without atypia</div><div><br/></div><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Section shows endometrial glands in _early secretory phase with focal areas exhibiting simple hyperplasia characterized by glandular branching and crowding. No malignancy is observed.</div><div><br/></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
